Loan Default Prediction

Problem Definition

The Context:

Loan defaults represent a significant risk to the profitability of retail banks, as non-performing assets (NPAs) can substantially impact their bottom line. According to banking industry reports, even a small reduction in default rates can translate to millions of dollars in saved revenue. Currently, the loan approval process is multifaceted and often manual, making it both effort-intensive and susceptible to human error and biases.

By developing a robust loan default prediction model, banks can:

  • Reduce the financial risk associated with bad loans/NPAs
  • Make the approval process more efficient and consistent (reducing approval time by 40-60%)
  • Remove human biases from the decision-making process
  • Improve the overall portfolio quality of home equity loans
  • Comply with regulatory requirements like the Equal Credit Opportunity Act
  • Create a competitive advantage through data-driven decision making
  • Free up loan officers to focus on complex cases requiring human judgment

The financial implications of improved loan default prediction are substantial, with potential to increase bank profitability by 15-20% in the consumer credit division.

The Objective:

The primary objectives of this project are to:

  • Build a classification model that accurately predicts which clients are likely to default on their home equity loans
  • Identify the key features that significantly influence loan default risk
  • Establish optimal thresholds for different risk tolerance levels
  • Provide actionable recommendations to the bank for improving their loan approval process
  • Create a model that is interpretable enough to provide justification for any adverse decisions (rejections)
  • Ensure the model follows regulatory guidelines and is free from discriminatory biases
  • Develop a framework for continuous model monitoring and improvement
  • Quantify the financial impact of the improved prediction model

The Key Questions:

  • What customer attributes and loan characteristics are most predictive of default risk?
  • How do demographic and financial factors influence the likelihood of loan default?
  • Are there specific patterns or customer segments that show higher default rates?
  • What interactions between variables significantly impact default probability?
  • What is the optimal threshold for approving loans that balances risk and business objectives?
  • How can the bank improve their current approval process to minimize defaults while maintaining a healthy loan portfolio?
  • What quantifiable impact can an improved model have on the bank's financial performance?
  • How do different model types perform on this specific loan default prediction task?
  • Which derived features or transformations provide additional predictive power?
  • How can we ensure the model remains effective over time with changing economic conditions?

The Problem Formulation:

We are developing a binary classification model to predict whether a loan applicant will default (BAD=1) or repay their loan (BAD=0) based on various applicant characteristics and loan attributes. The model will use historical data from past loan applicants who have been given credit, learning patterns that indicate higher default risk.

The solution must be:

  • Accurate in predicting defaults to minimize financial risk
  • Interpretable to satisfy regulatory requirements
  • Fair and unbiased across different customer segments
  • Operationally feasible for integration into the bank's decision process
  • Robust to changes in economic conditions and customer demographics
  • Capable of providing probability estimates, not just binary decisions
  • Designed to balance false positives (denying loans to creditworthy customers) and false negatives (approving loans that will default)

Data Description:

The Home Equity dataset (HMEQ) contains baseline and loan performance information for 5,960 recent home equity loans. The target (BAD) is a binary variable that indicates whether an applicant has ultimately defaulted or has been severely delinquent. This adverse outcome occurred in 1,189 cases (20 percent). 12 input variables were registered for each applicant.

  • BAD: 1 = Client defaulted on loan, 0 = loan repaid

  • LOAN: Amount of loan approved.

  • MORTDUE: Amount due on the existing mortgage.

  • VALUE: Current value of the property.

  • REASON: Reason for the loan request. (HomeImp = home improvement, DebtCon= debt consolidation which means taking out a new loan to pay off other liabilities and consumer debts)

  • JOB: The type of job that loan applicant has such as manager, self, etc.

  • YOJ: Years at present job.

  • DEROG: Number of major derogatory reports (which indicates a serious delinquency or late payments).

  • DELINQ: Number of delinquent credit lines (a line of credit becomes delinquent when a borrower does not make the minimum required payments 30 to 60 days past the day on which the payments were due).

  • CLAGE: Age of the oldest credit line in months.

  • NINQ: Number of recent credit inquiries.

  • CLNO: Number of existing credit lines.

  • DEBTINC: Debt-to-income ratio (all your monthly debt payments divided by your gross monthly income. This number is one way lenders measure your ability to manage the monthly payments to repay the money you plan to borrow.

def plot_numeric_histograms(df, numeric_cols, figsize=(16, 5*math.ceil(len(numeric_cols)/2))):
   """
   Create histograms for numeric columns arranged in subplots.
   Uses clean display names for titles and labels.

   Parameters:
   -----------
   df : pandas.DataFrame
       The dataframe containing the numeric columns to plot
   numeric_cols : list
       List of numeric column names to create histograms for
   figsize : tuple, optional
       Figure size as (width, height) in inches, default dynamically calculated based on column count
   """
   # Calculate layout dimensions
   n_plots = len(numeric_cols)
   n_cols = 2  # Show 2 plots per row
   n_rows = math.ceil(n_plots / n_cols)

   # Create the figure and subplots
   fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=figsize)
   axes = axes.flatten() if n_rows * n_cols > 1 else [axes]  # Flatten if multiple plots

   # Create a histogram for each numeric column
   for i, col in enumerate(numeric_cols):
       if i < len(axes):  # Ensure we don't exceed the number of subplots
           # Plot histogram with KDE (Kernel Density Estimation) curve
           sns.histplot(df[col], kde=True, ax=axes[i])
           axes[i].set_title(f'Distribution of {col}')
           axes[i].set_xlabel(col)
           axes[i].set_ylabel('Frequency')

   # Hide any unused subplots if odd number of columns
   for j in range(i+1, len(axes)):
       axes[j].set_visible(False)

   # Adjust spacing between subplots for better readability
   plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3, hspace=0.4)
   plt.tight_layout()
   plt.show()

# Generate histograms for all numeric variables to visualize their distributions
plot_numeric_histograms(df, numeric_cols)

  • DEBTINC (Debt-to-Income) Distribution:

    • Tightly concentrated between 25-50% representing typical borrower debt loads.
    • Very few borrowers fall below 20% or above 60%.
    • The clean bell shape differs notably from other variables, suggesting this metric may be standardized or normalized during underwriting.

def plot_categorical_bars(df, categorical_cols, figsize=(16, 5*math.ceil(len(categorical_cols)/2))):
   """
   Create stacked bar charts for categorical columns arranged in subplots.
   Each chart shows the distribution of loan defaults vs repayments by category.

   Parameters:
   -----------
   df : pandas.DataFrame
       The dataframe containing the categorical columns to plot
   categorical_cols : list
       List of categorical column names to create bar charts for
   figsize : tuple, optional
       Figure size as (width, height) in inches, default dynamically calculated based on column count
   """
   # Calculate layout dimensions
   n_plots = len(categorical_cols)
   n_cols = 2  # Show 2 plots per row
   n_rows = math.ceil(n_plots / n_cols)

   # Create the figure and subplots
   fig, axes = plt.subplots(n_rows, n_cols, figsize=figsize)
   axes = axes.flatten() if n_rows * n_cols > 1 else [axes]  # Flatten if multiple plots

   # Create a stacked bar chart for each categorical column
   for i, col in enumerate(categorical_cols):
       if i < len(axes):  # Ensure we don't exceed the number of subplots
           # Create cross-tabulation between the categorical variable and the target variable
           crosstab = pd.crosstab(df[col], df['BAD'])

           # Plot stacked bar chart showing distribution of defaults (1) vs non-defaults (0)
           crosstab.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=axes[i], color=['blue', 'red'])
           axes[i].set_title(f'{col} by Loan Default Status')
           axes[i].set_xlabel(col)
           axes[i].set_ylabel('Count')
           axes[i].tick_params(axis='x', rotation=45)
           axes[i].legend(['Loan Repaid', 'Loan Defaulted'])

   # Hide any unused subplots if odd number of columns
   for j in range(i+1, len(axes)):
       axes[j].set_visible(False)

   # Adjust spacing between subplots for better readability
   plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3, hspace=0.4)
   plt.tight_layout()
   plt.show()

# Generate stacked bar charts for categorical variables to visualize their relationship with loan defaults
plot_categorical_bars(df, categorical_cols)

Observations:

  • REASON by Loan Default Status:

    • Debt Consolidation Dominance: Debt consolidation is the more common loan reason, representing approximately twice as many loans as home improvements.
    • Default Rate Differences: Home improvement loans show a visibly higher proportion of defaults (red proportions) compared to debt consolidation loans (22.25% vs. 18.97%).
    • Distribution Pattern: Of the total sample, roughly 65-70% of loans are for debt consolidation, while 30-35% are for home improvements.
    • Risk Indication: The higher default rate for home improvement loans suggests this purpose may carry intrinsically higher risk, despite being less common overall.

  • JOB by Loan Default Status:

    • Occupational Distribution: "Other" is the most common job category, followed by "ProfExe" (Professional/Executive), with "Sales" being the least represented.
    • Default Rate Variation: Significant differences in default rates (red proportions) across job categories: (1) "Sales" and "Self" (self-employed) show the highest proportion of defaults, (2) "Office" appears to have the lowest proportion of defaults and (3) "Other" and "Mgr" (Manager) have moderate default rates.
    • Professional Advantage: The "ProfExe" category shows a relatively lower default rate compared to most other categories except "Office"
    • High-Risk Segments: The small but notable "Sales" and "Self" categories reveal substantially higher risk profiles, with nearly 30-35% of these loans defaulting
    • Volume vs. Risk Trade-off: While "Other" represents the highest volume of loans, it doesn't correspond to the highest default proportion, suggesting volume alone doesn't predict risk.

These patterns indicate that both loan purpose and occupation type are potentially important predictors for default risk, with clear variations across categories that should be incorporated into the modeling approach. The particularly high default rates for self-employed and sales professionals suggest these segments may warrant special attention during the loan approval process.

These boxplots provide visual distribution comparisons between defaulting and non-defaulting loans:

  • Credit Risk Variables (DEROG, DELINQ): Show dramatic differences with medians near zero for non-defaulters while defaulters show positive values. The boxplots reveal that defaulters (BAD=1) have significantly higher interquartile ranges for both variables, indicating that derogatory marks and delinquencies are strong predictors of default risk. The whiskers and outliers illustrate that even a single derogatory mark or delinquency substantially increases default risk.

CLAGE shows defaulters typically have newer credit histories (lower values), reinforcing that established credit reduces risk. The overlapping nature of the CLAGE distributions indicates this is a weaker predictor than DEROG or DELINQ.

Extreme outliers reaching dangerous debt-to-income levels over 100% appear exclusively in the defaulter group. CLNO (number of credit lines) shows minimal difference between groups, suggesting the quantity of credit lines alone is not strongly predictive of default.
  • Loan Characteristics: LOAN, MORTDUE, and VALUE show slightly lower medians for defaulters, confirming the unexpected pattern where smaller loans show higher default rates. This may reflect different risk assessment processes for different loan sizes or indicate that borrowers with less valuable properties and smaller mortgages face higher financial instability. The presence of high outliers in both groups suggests that loan size alone isn't deterministic for default.
  • Employment Stability: YOJ (Years on Job) distributions appear similar between defaulters and non-defaulters, with slightly lower values for defaulters. The substantial overlap suggests employment tenure may be a weaker predictor than credit history or debt-to-income ratio.

# Calculate and compare mean values of numeric features between defaulted and non-defaulted loans
# Group data by the target variable 'BAD' and calculate mean for each numeric column
default_stats = df.groupby('BAD')[numeric_cols].mean().T

# Rename columns for clarity (0=Non-Default, 1=Default)
default_stats.columns = ['Non-Default', 'Default']

# Calculate percentage difference between default and non-default means
# Formula: ((Default - Non-Default) / Non-Default) * 100
default_stats['Percent_Difference'] = (default_stats['Default'] - default_stats['Non-Default']) / default_stats['Non-Default'] * 100

Treating Outliers

The following analysis was used to determine treatment of outliers within the dataset:

  1. Credit Risk Indicators (DEROG, DELINQ, NINQ): High values represent legitimate high-risk borrowers and therefore should not be removed from the dataset. The extreme values (e.g., DELINQ > 5) are rare but highly predictive of default.

  2. CLAGE (Credit Age): The maximum value of 1,168 months(~97 years) is implausible and likely an error. Therefore it was decided to cap the maximum value at a reasonable threshold (e.g., 720 months/60 years), a higher cap was chosen as very long-term credit histories could exist. The large quanitity of zero values could have been misinterpreted as error or even missing value but since CLAGE is in unit months, they likely represent genuine new credit accounts less than one month old.

  3. DEBTINC (Debt-to-Income): High values exceed typical lending standards, however they can occur in rare instances. The maximum of 203% is unusual but possible for borrowers experiencing income fluctuations.

  4. Property Values and Loans (VALUE, MORTDUE, LOAN): All observed values are plausible in real estate markets. The maximum property value of USD855,909 is high but entirely realistic for luxury properties.

    • Log transformation will normalize their distributions while preserving their relative relationships

  5. YOJ (Years on Job): All values should be kept as they are plausible employment durations. Zero values represent newly employed individuals, an important risk segment.

  6. CLNO (Number of Credit Lines): Retain all values, while 71 credit lines is high, it's not impossible for someone with multiple trade lines, retail accounts, and historical accounts. Very high values may represent legitimate complex credit profiles rather than errors.

Note: all outlier treatment should be vetted with stakeholders and industry professionals to ensure that all plausible values are left intact and that the above proposed outlier treatment makes sense within the given context.

def treat_outliers(df):
    """
    Perform outlier treatment on the input DataFrame.

    Parameters:
    -----------
    df : pandas.DataFrame
        Input DataFrame containing the original features

    Returns:
    --------
    pandas.DataFrame
        DataFrame with outlier treatment applied
    """
    # Create a deep copy of the input DataFrame to avoid modifying the original data
    df_treated = df.copy()

    # Clip CLAGE (Credit Line Age) to a maximum of 720 months (60 years)
    df_treated['CLAGE'] = df_treated['CLAGE'].clip(upper=720)

    # Apply log transformation to selected numerical features
    # log1p is used to handle zero values and reduce the impact of extreme outliers
    # Transforms: LOAN, MORTDUE, and VALUE
    for col in ['LOAN', 'MORTDUE', 'VALUE']:
        df_treated[f'{col}_LOG'] = np.log1p(df_treated[col])

    return df_treated

# Apply outlier treatment to the DataFrame
df_treated = treat_outliers(df)

The following analysis was used to determine treatment of Missing values within the dataset:

  2. MORTDUE: 8.7% missing values, imputed using mortgage-to-value ratio where VALUE exists and remaining missing values substituted with overall median

  5. JOB: 4.7% missing values, create 'unknown' category for missing value treatment.
  6. YOJ: 8.6% missing values, median imputation by job category (i.e. JOB will indicate the nature of employment and therefore the likely number of years employed - taking the median of the YOJ for each JOB category can give a rough idea and help impute the missing YOJ data).
  7. DEROG: 11.9% missing values, zero imputation for missing value treatment (i.e. it is possible for a person to have no derogatory reports and therefore replacing with zero makes sense).
  8. DELINQ: 9.7% missing values, zero imputation for missing value treatment (i.e. it is possible for a person to have no delinquencies and therefore replacing with zero makes sense).
  9. CLAGE: 5.2% missing values, imputed using CLNO bins as primary predictor where exists (grouped by number of credit lines) and remaining missing values substituted with overall median
  10. NINQ: 8.6% missing values, zero imputation for missing value treatment (i.e. it is possible for a person to have no recent inquiries and therefore replacing with zero makes sense).
  11. CLNO: 3.7% missing values, imputed using MORTDUE bins as primary predictor where exists (grouped by mortgage amount) and remaining missing values substituted with overall median.
  12. DEBTINC: 21.3% missing values, model based imputation using other financial variables.

def treat_missing_values(df):
    """
    Comprehensive missing value imputation strategy for loan dataset

    Imputation methods:
    1. MORTDUE and VALUE: Leverage relationship between mortgage due and property value
    2. REASON and JOB: Replace missing values with 'Unknown'
    3. YOJ (Years on Job): Median imputation by job category
    4. DEROG, DELINQ, NINQ: Zero imputation
    5. CLNO: Targeted imputation based on mortgage amount bins
    6. CLAGE: Targeted imputation based on credit line number bins
    7. DEBTINC: Advanced model-based imputation using Random Forest

    Returns:
    --------
    pandas.DataFrame
        DataFrame with missing values comprehensively treated
    """
    # Create a deep copy to prevent modifying the original DataFrame
    df_treated = df.copy()

    # 2-3. MORTDUE and VALUE - Handle missing values using their inherent relationship
    # Calculate median ratio between mortgage due and property value
    mtv_ratio = df.loc[df['MORTDUE'].notna() & df['VALUE'].notna(), 'MORTDUE'].median() / \
            df.loc[df['MORTDUE'].notna() & df['VALUE'].notna(), 'VALUE'].median()

    # Impute MORTDUE where VALUE is available
    # Uses the calculated ratio to estimate missing mortgage due amount
    mask = df_treated['MORTDUE'].isna() & df_treated['VALUE'].notna()
    df_treated.loc[mask, 'MORTDUE'] = df_treated.loc[mask, 'VALUE'] * mtv_ratio

    # Impute VALUE where MORTDUE is available
    # Reverse of previous imputation using inverse of the ratio
    mask = df_treated['VALUE'].isna() & df_treated['MORTDUE'].notna()
    df_treated.loc[mask, 'VALUE'] = df_treated.loc[mask, 'MORTDUE'] / mtv_ratio

    # Fill remaining missing MORTDUE and VALUE with their respective medians
    df_treated['MORTDUE'] = df_treated['MORTDUE'].fillna(df_treated['MORTDUE'].median())
    df_treated['VALUE'] = df_treated['VALUE'].fillna(df_treated['VALUE'].median())

    # 4-5. REASON and JOB - Replace missing categorical values with 'Unknown'
    df_treated['REASON'] = df_treated['REASON'].fillna('Unknown')
    df_treated['JOB'] = df_treated['JOB'].fillna('Unknown')

    # 6. YOJ (Years on Job) - Median imputation by job category
    # This approach preserves job-specific employment patterns
    df_treated['YOJ'] = df_treated.groupby('JOB', observed=True)['YOJ'].transform(
        lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
    # Fallback to overall median if any missing values remain
    df_treated['YOJ'] = df_treated['YOJ'].fillna(df_treated['YOJ'].median())

    # 7, 8 & 10. DEROG, DELINQ, NINQ - Zero imputation
    # Assumes missing values indicate no negative events
    for col in ['DEROG', 'DELINQ', 'NINQ']:
        df_treated[col] = df_treated[col].fillna(0)

    # 11. CLNO (Credit Line Number) - Targeted imputation based on mortgage amount
    if df_treated['CLNO'].isna().sum() > 0:
        # Create mortgage amount bins for more precise imputation
        df_treated['MORTDUE_BIN'] = pd.cut(df_treated['MORTDUE'],
                                        bins=[0, 50000, 100000, 150000, 500000],
                                        labels=['0-50k', '50k-100k', '100k-150k', '150k+'])

        # Impute CLNO using median within mortgage amount groups
        df_treated['CLNO'] = df_treated.groupby('MORTDUE_BIN', observed=True)['CLNO'].transform(
            lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
        df_treated.drop('MORTDUE_BIN', axis=1, inplace=True)

        # Fallback to overall median if any missing values persist
        df_treated['CLNO'] = df_treated['CLNO'].fillna(df_treated['CLNO'].median())

    # 12. CLAGE (Credit Line Age) - Targeted imputation based on credit line number
    if df_treated['CLAGE'].isna().sum() > 0:
        # Create credit line number bins for precise imputation
        df_treated['CLNO_BIN'] = pd.cut(df_treated['CLNO'],
                                       bins=[0, 10, 20, 30, 100],
                                       labels=['0-10', '10-20', '20-30', '30+'])

        # Impute CLAGE using median within credit line groups
        df_treated['CLAGE'] = df_treated.groupby('CLNO_BIN', observed=True)['CLAGE'].transform(
            lambda x: x.fillna(x.median()))
        df_treated.drop('CLNO_BIN', axis=1, inplace=True)

        # Fallback to overall median if any missing values remain
        df_treated['CLAGE'] = df_treated['CLAGE'].fillna(df_treated['CLAGE'].median())

    # 13. DEBTINC (Debt to Income Ratio) - Advanced model-based imputation
    if df_treated['DEBTINC'].isna().sum() > 0:
        # Separate DataFrame into rows with and without missing DEBTINC
        df_missing = df_treated[df_treated['DEBTINC'].isna()].copy()
        df_complete = df_treated[df_treated['DEBTINC'].notna()].copy()

        # Select predictive features for DEBTINC
        predictors = ['LOAN', 'MORTDUE', 'VALUE', 'CLNO', 'CLAGE']

        # Use Random Forest Regressor for sophisticated imputation
        from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestRegressor
        model = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=100, random_state=42)
        model.fit(df_complete[predictors], df_complete['DEBTINC'])

        # Predict missing DEBTINC values
        df_missing['DEBTINC'] = model.predict(df_missing[predictors])

        # Recombine and sort to maintain original index
        df_treated = pd.concat([df_complete, df_missing]).sort_index()

    # Handle log-transformed columns to ensure no missing values
    for col in df_treated.columns:
        if col.endswith('_LOG') and df_treated[col].isna().sum() > 0:
            original_col = col.replace('_LOG', '')
            if original_col in df_treated.columns:
                # Reapply log1p transformation for any missing log columns
                df_treated[col] = np.log1p(df_treated[original_col])

    return df_treated

# Apply comprehensive missing value treatment
df_treated = treat_missing_values(df_treated)

# Display first few rows to verify transformations
df_treated.head()

Important Insights from EDA

What are the the most important observations and insights from the data based on the EDA performed?

Loan default prediction is driven by credit history quality, financial stability, and applicant characteristics that interact in complex ways. The strongest predictors are delinquent credit lines (DELINQ) and derogatory reports (DEROG), with 400%+ higher values in defaulting loans. Clear threshold effects exist for several variables, particularly the powerful interaction between occupation and loan purpose. The data suggests a multi-faceted approach combining binary exclusion rules for severe credit issues, graduated scoring for financial metrics, and targeted policies for high-risk combinations of characteristics.

def metrics_score(actual, predicted):
    """
    Evaluate model performance through comprehensive metrics visualization.

    Parameters:
    -----------
    actual : array-like
        True labels/ground truth values
    predicted : array-like
        Model's predicted labels

    Outputs:
    --------
    Classification Report:
        - Precision
        - Recall
        - F1-Score
        - Support for each class

    Confusion Matrix Visualization:
        - Heatmap showing prediction accuracy
        - Annotated with prediction counts
    """
    print(classification_report(actual, predicted))

    cm = confusion_matrix(actual, predicted)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 5))
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f', xticklabels=['Not Converted', 'Converted'],
                yticklabels=['Not Converted', 'Converted'])
    plt.ylabel('Actual')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.title('Confusion Matrix')
    plt.show()
In[]:
def model_performance_classification(model, predictors, target):
    """
    Evaluate classification model performance using key metrics.

    Parameters:
    -----------
    model : object
        Trained machine learning classification model
    predictors : array-like
        Input features used for prediction
    target : array-like
        True target labels

    Returns:
    --------
    pandas.DataFrame
        Performance metrics including:
        - Precision (macro average)
        - Recall (macro average)
        - Accuracy
    """
    # Predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    recall = recall_score(target, pred, average='macro')  # To compute recall
    precision = precision_score(target, pred, average='macro')  # To compute precision
    acc = accuracy_score(target, pred)  # To compute accuracy score

    # Creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "Precision": precision,
            "Recall": recall,
            "Accuracy": acc,
        },
        index=[0],
    )

    return df_perf

Decision Tree - Hyperparameter Tuning

  • Hyperparameter tuning is tricky in the sense that there is no direct way to calculate how a change in the hyperparameter value will reduce the loss of your model, so we usually resort to experimentation. We'll use Grid search to perform hyperparameter tuning.
  • Grid search is a tuning technique that attempts to compute the optimum values of hyperparameters.
  • It is an exhaustive search that is performed on the specific parameter values of a model.
  • The parameters of the estimator/model used to apply these methods are optimized by cross-validated grid-search over a parameter grid.

Criterion {gini, entropy}

The function to measure the quality of a split. Supported criteria are gini for the Gini impurity and entropy for the information gain.

max_depth

The maximum depth of the tree. If None, then nodes are expanded until all leaves are pure or until all leaves contain less than min_samples_split samples.

min_samples_leaf

The minimum number of samples is required to be at a leaf node. A split point at any depth will only be considered if it leaves at least min_samples_leaf training samples in each of the left and right branches. This may have the effect of smoothing the model, especially in regression.

You can learn about more Hyperpapameters on this link and try to tune them.

https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier.html

In[]:
dtree_estimator = DecisionTreeClassifier(class_weight=class_weights, random_state=42)

# Grid of parameters to choose from
parameters = {'max_depth': np.arange(2, 7),
              'criterion': ['gini', 'entropy'],
              'min_samples_leaf': [5, 10, 20, 25]
             }

# Type of scoring used to compare parameter combinations
scorer = metrics.make_scorer(recall_score, pos_label=1)

print("\nPerforming grid search for hyperparameter tuning...")
# Run the grid search with 5-fold cross-validation
gridCV = GridSearchCV(dtree_estimator, parameters, scoring=scorer, cv=5, n_jobs=-1)

# Fit the grid search on the training data
gridCV = gridCV.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train)

# Print the best parameters and best score
print("\nBest parameters found by grid search:")
print(gridCV.best_params_)
print(f"Best cross-validation score: {gridCV.best_score_:.4f}")

# Set the classifier to the best combination of parameters
optimized_dt = gridCV.best_estimator_

print(f"Selected criterion: {optimized_dt.criterion}")
print(f"Min samples leaf: {optimized_dt.min_samples_leaf}")

  • Confusion Matrix Changes: False negatives decreased from 133 to 51 (better at catching conversions), but false positives increased dramatically from 280 to 830 (many non-converting loans incorrectly flagged as likely to convert).

Random Forest Classifier

Random Forest is a bagging algorithm where the base models are Decision Trees. Samples are taken from the training data and on each sample a decision tree makes a prediction.

The results from all the decision trees are combined together and the final prediction is made using voting or averaging.

  • Confusion Matrix Insights: From the training set we saw 3340 true negatives, 832 true positives, with 0 false positives and 0 false negatives (perfect classification) and from the testing set we saw 1424 true negatives, 197 true positives, with 7 false positives and 160 false negatives. The model achieves excellent precision (97% for converted loans) but misses a significant number of actual conversions (45% of converted loans are not captured).
  • Feature Importance: The random forest uses a more balanced distribution of features than the decision trees. The top features are CLAGE (11.3%), DELINQ (10.6%), and DEBTINC (10.5%), followed by LOAN_LOG (7.6%) and LOAN (7.2%). Unlike the decision trees that relied heavily on 2-3 features, the random forest leverages information from many variables, with the top 10 features all contributing meaningfully to predictions.

# Visualizing model performance specifically for default prediction (positive class)

# Function to calculate default-specific metrics
def calculate_default_metrics(model, X_test, y_test):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)

    # Calculate metrics specifically for the default class (positive class, label=1)
    precision = precision_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=1)
    recall = recall_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=1)
    f1 = f1_score(y_test, y_pred, pos_label=1)

    # Calculate true positives and false positives from confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_test, y_pred)
    if len(cm) > 1:  # Ensure we have both classes in predictions
        tn, fp, fn, tp = cm.ravel()
        true_positive_rate = tp / (tp + fn)
        false_positive_rate = fp / (fp + tn)
    else:
        true_positive_rate = 0
        false_positive_rate = 0

    return precision, recall, f1, true_positive_rate, false_positive_rate

# Calculate default prediction metrics for all models
models = [log_reg, dt, optimized_dt, rf, rf_tuned, gb, optimized_gb]
model_names = ['Logistic Regression', 'Decision Tree', 'Optimized Decision Tree',
               'Random Forest', 'Optimized Random Forest', 'Gradient Boosting',
               'Optimized Gradient Boosting']

default_precision = []
default_recall = []
default_f1 = []
tpr = []
fpr = []

for model in models:
    precision, recall, f1, tp_rate, fp_rate = calculate_default_metrics(model, X_test_scaled, y_test)
    default_precision.append(precision)
    default_recall.append(recall)
    default_f1.append(f1)
    tpr.append(tp_rate)
    fpr.append(fp_rate)

# Create DataFrame for easy comparison
metrics_df = pd.DataFrame({
    'Model': model_names,
    'Precision (Default)': [round(p, 4) for p in default_precision],
    'Recall (Default)': [round(r, 4) for r in default_recall],
    'F1 Score (Default)': [round(f, 4) for f in default_f1],
    'True Positive Rate': [round(t, 4) for t in tpr],
    'False Positive Rate': [round(f, 4) for f in fpr]
})

    missed_defaults.append(missed)
    false_alarms.append(false_alarm)
    correct_approvals.append(correct_approval)

Comprehensive Model Comparison:

  • Accuracy Performance: Optimized Random Forest leads (91.3%), followed closely by Optimized Gradient Boosting (90.0%), Basic Random Forest (90.7%), and Basic Gradient Boosting (88.0%). Logistic Regression (77.6%) and Basic Decision Tree (76.9%) show similar mid-range performance, while Optimized Decision Tree significantly underperforms (50.7%).
  • Precision Performance: Basic Random Forest achieves the highest precision (93.2%), with Optimized Random Forest (89.9%) and both Gradient Boosting models (Basic: 89.0%, Optimized: 88.0%) close behind. The remaining models show moderate precision: Logistic Regression (68.0%), Basic Decision Tree (67.0%), and Optimized Decision Tree (59.6%).
  • Recall Performance: Optimized Decision Tree demonstrates the highest recall (85.0%) for defaults, followed by Optimized Random Forest (65.0%), Basic Random Forest (55.0%), Optimized Gradient Boosting (57.0%), and Basic Gradient Boosting (44.0%). Logistic Regression (65.0%) and Basic Decision Tree (63.0%) show moderate recall.
  • Model Complexity & Performance: A clear pattern emerges where more complex models (Random Forests and Gradient Boosting) significantly outperform simpler models (Logistic Regression, Decision Trees). The linear approach (Logistic Regression) performs notably worse than the best non-linear methods, indicating that loan default patterns likely involve complex interactions between borrower characteristics that linear models cannot adequately capture. However, this performance gain comes with reduced interpretability, creating an important consideration for regulatory compliance contexts.
  • Class Imbalance Handling: Random Forest and Gradient Boosting models demonstrate superior ability to handle the dataset's class imbalance (80% non-default vs. 20% default loans), maintaining strong performance on both classes. The Optimized Decision Tree's attempt to improve minority class detection led to severe overprediction of defaults and substantially reduced accuracy.
  • Feature Utilization: Ensemble models (Random Forest and Gradient Boosting) make better use of available features, distributing importance across a wider range of variables, while Decision Trees concentrate heavily on just 2-3 features. Notably, all models identify DELINQ, CLAGE, and DEBTINC as key predictors, with ensemble methods also recognizing the importance of DEROG and loan characteristics.
  • Overall Assessment: Ensemble models substantially outperform alternative approaches across most metrics. For a balanced approach, Optimized Random Forest offers the best overall performance. For maximum default detection, Optimized Decision Tree captures the most potential defaults but at the cost of many false positives. A dual-model approach using both would provide the most comprehensive risk assessment framework.

Questions Answered

1. Comparison of various techniques and their relative performance based on chosen Metric (Measure of success):

Among the seven models evaluated for loan default prediction, the Optimized Random Forest demonstrated the best overall performance with 91.3% accuracy, strong precision (89.9%), and excellent recall (65.0% for defaults). This model provides the best balance between identifying potential defaults and minimizing false alarms, achieving the highest F1-score (75.0%) for the default class. The Basic Random Forest followed closely with 90.7% accuracy and high precision (93.2%), but with lower recall for defaults (55.0%).

The Gradient Boosting models showed strong performance, with the Optimized version achieving 90.0% accuracy and a good balance for default prediction (88.0% precision, 57.0% recall, 69.0% F1-score). This positions it as a strong alternative to the Random Forest models.

The Logistic Regression and Basic Decision Tree showed comparable mid-range performance (77.6% and 76.9% accuracy respectively), while the Optimized Decision Tree sacrificed significant overall accuracy (50.7%) to maximize default detection, achieving the highest recall for defaults (85.0%) but with extremely low precision (27.0%).

For default detection specificallythe most critical metric for minimizing financial riska dual-model approach appears optimal. The Optimized Random Forest provides the best overall balance with high accuracy and F1-score, while the Optimized Decision Tree could serve as a secondary screening tool to catch potential defaults that might be missed by the primary model. There is scope for further improvement through:

  • Feature engineering focusing on the most predictive variables identified across models: DELINQ, CLAGE, DEBTINC, and DEROG
  • Implementing a tiered approach where low-risk applications are processed automatically, while high-risk cases receive additional review
  • Cost-sensitive learning that more precisely calibrates the model to the specific financial impact of missed defaults versus rejected good loans

2. Refined insights: The most meaningful insights for loan default prediction from this analysis are:

  • Credit history quality dominates default prediction: Delinquencies (DELINQ), credit age (CLAGE), debt-to-income ratio (DEBTINC), and derogatory reports (DEROG) consistently emerged as the strongest predictors across all models. Both Random Forest and Gradient Boosting models revealed these factors account for over 40% of predictive power, with DELINQ (13-22%) and CLAGE (10-16%) being particularly influential.
  • Model complexity matters significantly: The substantial performance gap between ensemble models (88-91% accuracy) and simpler models (77-78% accuracy) demonstrates that default patterns involve complex interactions between variables that cannot be adequately captured by linear or simple tree-based approaches.
  • Feature importance distribution varies by model type: While Decision Trees concentrated almost all importance in 2-3 variables, ensemble methods (Random Forests and Gradient Boosting) distributed importance more evenly across features, suggesting these approaches capture subtle patterns ignored by simpler models. Notably, Gradient Boosting recognized the importance of employment stability (YOJ) and number of credit lines (CLNO) more than other models.
  • Performance trade-offs are business-critical: The Optimized Decision Tree's attempt to maximize default detection led to severe overprediction (accuracy dropping from 77% to 51%), highlighting that blindly optimizing for a single metric (recall) without considering precision can lead to impractical models with excessive false positives. The Optimized Gradient Boosting model demonstrated that it's possible to substantially improve recall (44% to 57%) without significant precision loss.
  • Class imbalance handling requires sophistication: The imbalanced nature of default data creates challenges that only the more sophisticated models could effectively address. Ensemble methods demonstrated superior ability to maintain strong performance on both the majority and minority classes without resorting to extreme overprediction.

3. Proposal for the final solution design:

I propose a tiered approach using the Optimized Random Forest as the primary model, supplemented by risk indicators from the Decision Tree for high-risk segments. This hybrid approach offers several advantages:

  • Balanced performance: The Optimized Random Forest provides the best overall accuracy (91.3%) while maintaining strong default detection (81.7% recall).
  • Risk segmentation capability: The solution should leverage the probability scores from the Random Forest to create three distinct risk tiers:
    • Low-risk loans (default probability <10%): Fast-tracked for approval with minimal additional screening
    • Medium-risk loans (10-30%): Enhanced review focusing on the key risk factors (DELINQ, CLAGE, DEBTINC)
    • High-risk loans (>30%): Declined or requiring substantial additional documentation/collateral
  • Regulatory compliance: While Random Forests offer superior performance, their "black box" nature presents challenges for providing rejection justifications. The key features identified (particularly DELINQ, CLAGE, and DEBTINC) provide clear, interpretable criteria that can be communicated to applicants and regulators.
  • Operational flexibility: This approach allows the bank to adjust risk tolerance based on economic conditionsrelaxing or tightening the threshold criteria without retraining the primary model.
  • Actionable insights: The model structure directly translates to practical underwriting guidelines, with special attention to delinquency history, credit age, and debt-to-income ratio thresholds that have been shown to significantly impact default risk.

This solution balances statistical performance with business needs, offering both strong predictive power and the interpretability required for effective implementation in a regulated lending environment.

Executive Summary

The analysis of home equity loan data has led to the development of a data-driven default prediction model that can significantly enhance the bank's risk management capabilities. Based on the findings from the loan dataset, several key patterns have emerged:

  • Credit history quality emerged as the dominant predictor of loan default, with delinquent credit lines (DELINQ) and derogatory reports (DEROG) showing 427% and 401% higher values respectively in defaulting loans. This finding enables more targeted risk assessment for applicants with credit issues.
  • Pronounced threshold effects were identified across key financial variables, most notably in debt-to-income ratio (DEBTINC), where default risk triples from 5.7% to 17.8% when exceeding 39%providing a clear decision boundary for underwriting standards.
  • Occupation-purpose interactions revealed unexpected risk concentrations, with self-employed borrowers seeking debt consolidation showing an alarming 43.8% default ratemore than twice the risk of self-employed borrowers seeking home improvement loans (18.3%). This insight enables more precise treatment of specific applicant segments.
  • Credit maturity impact demonstrated a strong linear relationship with default risk, where each increasing quintile of credit age (CLAGE) is associated with approximately 5% reduction in default rate decreasing from 30% default rate for newest credit histories to just 10% for the most established accounts.

The recommended implementation is a dual-model approach using a Random Forest Classifier that achieved 91% accuracy on the test dataset with solid precision-recall balance. This ensemble model maintains strong predictive performance (F1-score of 0.94 for non-defaults and 0.70 for defaults) while providing transparent insights through feature importance rankings. The model identifies credit age (CLAGE), delinquent credit lines (DELINQ), and debt-to-income ratio (DEBTINC) as the three most influential factors, enabling clearer lending decisions.

For high-risk detection scenarios where missing potential defaults carries elevated costs, an optimized Decision Tree model can serve as a secondary screening layer. This model captures 86% of all defaults (compared to 55-63% in traditional models) using a transparent, rules-based structure focused solely on three credit history variables, making it suitable for regulatory compliance and customer explanation purposes.

Problem and Solution Summary

Problem Context

Loan defaults represent a significant financial concern for retail banks, with non-performing assets (NPAs) directly affecting profitability and capital reserves. The dataset analysis reveals a 20% default rate on home equity loans. The current loan approval process appears to be largely manual, with potential inconsistencies in decision criteria across loan officers, which may lead to extended processing times and difficulties in identifying high-risk applicants based on data-driven insights.

Problem Dimensions

  • Financial risk exposure is a key concern as NPAs reduce profitability through write-offs, provisioning requirements, and collection costs. With an average loan amount of $18,608 and 20% default rate across 5,960 loans in the dataset, approximately $22.4 million in loan value is at risk. Improvements in default prediction could potentially reduce this exposure significantly.
  • Process inefficiency is another challenge as manual, document-heavy approvals likely create processing bottlenecks, inconsistent risk assessments, and friction in customer experience. A more streamlined, data-driven process could improve approval timelines and consistency while reducing operational costs.
  • Regulatory compliance requirements must be considered as the Equal Credit Opportunity Act mandates non-discriminatory, verifiable lending decisions with clear justification for adverse actions. A more objective, data-driven evaluation process could provide better documentation and consistency, enhancing the bank's compliance posture.
  • Resource allocation could be optimized as loan officers may currently spend significant time on routine application reviews rather than focusing on complex cases, relationship building, and exception handling. Automation of routine assessments could free up these valuable resources for higher-value activities.

Solution Design: Data-Driven Risk Assessment System

The proposed solution leverages analytics and machine learning to enhance the loan approval process through four complementary components:

  • Dual-model risk assessment approach forms the foundation of the solution, combining a Random Forest model with 91% accuracy for balanced precision-recall in standard risk assessment with a high-sensitivity Decision Tree model capturing 86% of defaults for enhanced risk detection. This approach is complemented by explainability tools that provide feature importance analysis and decision path visualization to support regulatory compliance. Integration methods with existing loan origination systems would ensure workflow efficiency.
  • Risk segmentation strategy targets specific combinations of applicant characteristics with higher default probability. The analysis identified several high-risk segments including self-employed applicants seeking debt consolidation (43.8% default rate), sales professionals regardless of loan purpose (34.2% average default rate), applicants with any delinquencies (significantly higher baseline default risk), and new employees with high debt-to-income ratios. Each segment would receive customized verification requirements and approval thresholds.
  • Data-driven decision framework establishes empirically derived cutoffs for key variables based on the analysis. For delinquencies (DELINQ), the difference between 0 and 1+ delinquencies represents a jump from 17% to 55% default rate. For debt-to-income ratio (DEBTINC), the threshold of 39% separates lower-risk borrowers (6% default rate) from higher-risk ones (18% default rate). Credit age (CLAGE) shows a clear pattern with <100 months associated with 30% default rate compared to just 10% for borrowers with >250 months of credit history. These thresholds would be incorporated into a weighted risk scoring system.
  • Performance monitoring system would track how predictions compare to actual outcomes, enabling regular model recalibration to adapt to changing conditions. Ongoing testing of model refinements would ensure optimal performance over time and help identify when adjustments are needed.
